According to the content of the article, the main reasons for NBC’s repeated acquisition and loss of major league baseball rights are as follows:
One is that the baseball league's asking price for broadcast rights continues to increase, and NBC is unwilling to pay high prices for contract renewal;
The second is that NBC wants to focus on the development of broadcast rights for other sports, such as NFL and NBA, so it no longer pays attention to baseball broadcast rights;
The third is NBC's program strategy adjustment, hoping to arrange other types of programs during the baseball broadcast time period to strive for higher ratings;
Fourth, the baseball league hopes that broadcasting rights will be transferred between different TV networks in turn to obtain higher overall broadcasting fees;
Fifth, the changes in NBC's internal personnel during a certain period of time have led to a reduction in the importance attached to baseball broadcasts;
Sixth, the influence of the baseball league has declined, and the ratings have been poor, resulting in damage to NBC's performance and reducing interest in baseball broadcast rights;
Seventh, competition among emerging media has intensified. For example, Fox and ESPN have joined the bidding for broadcast rights, and broadcast fees have risen sharply. NBC is unwilling to pay high prices;
Finally, there are some undisclosed commercial factors, such as the payment period of royalties and the selection of specific events, which are inconsistent in negotiations.
On the whole, the main reasons are cost considerations, business adjustment strategies, and the influence of baseball league rights maximization, which led to NBC giving up and regaining the broadcasting rights many times, but NBC’s interest in baseball broadcasting has always existed.
